defaultWritten Submission from defaultProf Tim Benton, University of LeedsdefaultSummarydefaultThe UK’s food security can be improved by (a) increasing productivity and its resilience locally, (b) increasing the resilience of the international food supply chain, accounting for 40-50% of our food use, (c) reducing waste of food already grown/imported, (d) helping people manage diets and dietary choices better, and reducing over-consumption.  Arguably, greater impacts on local food security will arise from (b-d) than from increasing productivity locally.  Ensuring both sustainability and resilience are key issues, even if they “cost” in yield terms.  Taking a food systems view is crucial in planning for a world made more variable by climate and where food and other resources are increasingly competed for.
defaultIntroductory comment
defaults
defaultThe relationship between the price of food and the cost of producing it;defaultThe implications of volatility in global food supply and demand for UK food security;defaultHow best to improve UK (and EU) food security, including using resources more efficiently;defaultWhether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food security strategies and planning; defaultWays of increasing self-defaultsufficiency in products for which the UK has a comparative advantagedefaultThe potential value and contribution of science and GM technology to UK food security.defaultHow food and farming supply chains, and the current systems for traceability,default&#xa0;default can contribute to increased resilience;defaultThe obstacles facing food producers, including small farmers, seeking to increase productdefaultion and access new markets; defaultConcluding remarksdefaultEconomic growth and ensuring a reliable and sustainable food supply are both important aims.  Encouraging healthy dietary choices and reducing waste – and thereby decreasing demand – has the potential to drive a “win-win-win” (health, environment, food security) solution.  This potentially allows producers to be paid more for producing less, but in a more environmentally sustainable way.  The UK has a strong potential to lead a “race to the top” to show that food systems for “sustainable nutrition” are both possible and profitable.  Thus, food security, for the UK (and globally) is not about producing more and more cheaply and accepting unsustainability: it is about encouraging respect for food, reducing waste, and managing production to protect the environment to allow our children and grandchildren to have the same securities we have now.
defaultDecember 2013
